In TypeScript, you can use the `asserts` clause of the `asserts` modifier to tell the type system that a value should be treated as having a specific type, even though it could potentially be of multiple types. This is useful when you have a function that returns a union type, but you want to use the function's return value as if it were a single, more specific type.

Here's an example:

```typescript
function getUser(): User | null {
  // ... some logic to fetch a user
  return user;
}

function requireUser() {
  const user = getUser();
  user.name; // TypeScript will not allow this because user could be null
  user.posts.length; // TypeScript will not allow this because user could be undefined
}

function requireUserAssert(user: User | null): asserts user is User {
  if (user === null) {
    throw new Error("User cannot be null");
  }
}

function useUser() {
  const user = getUser();
  requireUserAssert(user); // This assertion tells TypeScript that user is guaranteed to be a User

  user.name; // Now TypeScript knows user is a User and allows this
  user.posts.length; // TypeScript also allows this because user is asserted to be a User
}
```

In the `requireUserAssert` function, the `asserts` clause is used to assert that the `user` argument is a `User`. This assertion does not change the type of `user` at runtime; it only tells the TypeScript compiler that you have checked for the condition at runtime and that the type of `user` should be considered as a `User` for the purposes of type checking.

If you want to use a type guard function to assert the type, you can do something like this:

```typescript
function isUser(value: User | null): value is User {
  return value !== null;
}

function useUser() {
  const user = getUser();
  if (isUser(user)) {
    user.name; // TypeScript allows this because of the type guard
    user.posts.length; // TypeScript also allows this
  }
}
```

The `isUser` function is a type guard that checks if the `User | null` value is actually a `User`. When you use the result of this type guard in an if statement, the type of `user` within the if block is narrowed to `User`, allowing you to access properties specific to `User` without any type errors.

Remember that type assertions and type guard functions are runtime checks that can affect the performance of your code. They should be used judiciously and only when you can guarantee that the value will be of the asserted type.

